SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT
THIS SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (???Agreement???) is entered into on October 9, 2023 (the ???Effective Date???), by and among (i) Iris Solar, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (???Co-Owner 1???) and Sunlight Road Solar, L.L.C., a Delaware limited liability company (???Co-Owner 2???; each of Co- Owner 2 and Co-Owner 1 is sometimes referred to herein individually as a ???Co-Owner??? and collectively as ???Co-Owners???) and (ii) Co-Owner 1, in its capacity as the initial operator of the Shared Facilities (the ???Operator???). The Co-Owner and Operator are sometimes referred to collectively as the ???Parties??? and each, separately as a ???Party???.
RECITALS
WHEREAS, the Co-Owners and its Affiliates are developing and have developed solar powered alternative energy electric generating facilities located on real property in Washington Parish, Louisiana (each of which is referred to herein as a ???Facility??? and collectively as the ???Facilities???), each with a nameplate capacity of approximately:
Co-Owner 1 Facility: 50 MWAC Co-Owner 2 Facility: 50 MWAC
WHEREAS, the Co-Owners wish to own or will own undivided interests in certain personal property acquired or to be acquired for their respective Facilities and wish to further share the use and cost of certain electrical transmission, communications?? structures and other facilities and associated real property rights, and to engage the Operator to operate, maintain, repair and manage the foregoing, all in accordance with and subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement.
NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the recitals, the premises, covenants and conditions contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which the Parties acknowledge, the Parties agree as follows:
ARTICLE I -- DEFINITIONS, INTERPRETATIONS AND EXHIBITS
1.1 Definitions. As used in this Agreement, including the Recitals, and except as required by grammatical usage and apart from proper nouns, each capitalized term has the meaning given to it in this Agreement and in the Schedule of Definitions attached as Exhibit A.
1.2 Interpretation. In this Agreement, unless a clear, contrary intention appears: (a) the singular includes the plural and vice versa; (b) reference to any Person includes such Person???s successors and assigns but, in the case of a Party, only if such assigns are permitted by this Agreement, and reference to a Person in a particular capacity excludes such Person in any other capacity; (c) reference to any gender includes each other gender; (d) reference to any agreement (including this Agreement), document or instrument means such agreement, document or instrument as amended or modified and in effect from time to time in accordance with the terms thereof and, if applicable, the terms of this Agreement; (e) reference to any Law means such Law as amended, modified, codified, or reenacted, in whole or in part, and in effect from time to time, including, if applicable, rules and regulations promulgated thereunder; (f) reference to any Section means such Section of this Agreement, and references in any Section or definition to any clause means such clause of such Section or definition; (g) ???hereunder,??? ???hereof,??? 1
???hereto??? and words of similar import shall be deemed references to this Agreement as a whole and not to any particular Section or other provision of this Agreement; (h) ???including??? means including without limiting the generality of any description such term; and (i) relative to the determination of any period of time, ???from??? means ???from and including???, ???to??? means ???to be excluding??? and ???through??? means ???through and including???.
1.3 Incorporation of Recitals and Exhibits. The Recitals set forth in this Agreement and the Exhibits attached hereto are incorporated into this Agreement by reference for all purposes.
ARTICLE II -- TERM OF AGREEMENT
2.1 Term. This Agreement shall become effective as of the Effective Date and, subject to Applicable Laws, shall remain in force and effect until the earlier of (a) the date that is thirty (30) years after the Effective Date, and (b) the retirement and final disposition of all components of the Shared Facilities.
2.2 Payments on Termination. Upon termination of this Agreement, each Co-Owner shall pay Operator for its share, in proportion to its Undivided Use Interest at the time of such termination as set forth herein this Agreement, of any remaining balance owed for Operator???s costs incurred or irrevocably committed to be incurred pursuant to this Agreement as of the date of termination, within sixty (60) days following receipt of an invoice from Operator requiring such payment; provided that Operator shall use commercially reasonable efforts to minimize such costs.
2.3 Survival. Any obligations of a Party to any other Party, including payment obligations and indemnity obligations, as a result of this Agreement which accrued prior to or as a result of termination of this Agreement shall survive termination of this Agreement.
ARTICLE III -- SHARED FACILITIES AND REAL PROPERTY
3.1 Shared Facilities. The Co-Owners plan to procure, install and construct, or have procured, installed and constructed, certain facilities for electrical transmission, communications?? structures and other facilities, as described in Exhibit B, which may be altered or reconstructed by amendment in accordance with this Agreement, for shared use by the Co-Owners (collectively, the ???Shared Facilities???). Each grouping of Shared Facilities is described in Exhibit B (each a ???Shared Facilities Group???). For the avoidance of doubt, the Parties hereby agree and acknowledge that the Co-Owner 1 Solely Owned Property and the Co-Owner 2 Solely Owned Property shall not constitute Shared Facilities.
3.2 Shared Real Property. The Shared Facilities in each Shared Facilities Group are or will be located on certain real property (collectively, the ???Shared Real Property???) that is subject to the easement, lease, option or other rights and obligations in the documents described under the applicable section of Exhibit B (collectively, the ???Real Property Agreements???).
3.3 Shared Assets Groups. Each Shared Facilities Group, combined with the Shared Real Property corresponding to the Shared Facilities in such Shared Facilities Group (???Shared Assets???) described under the same section in Exhibit B shall be referred to herein as a ???Shared Assets Group???.
2
3.4 Access. Each Co-Owner shall have a non-exclusive right of access (a) to the Shared Facilities in which it has an Undivided Use Interest as necessary in order to ensure that Operator is meeting its obligations with respect to operation, maintenance and repair of such Shared Facilities, that Co-Owner???s Facility remains operational, and for the purposes contemplated in Article VII; and (b) over any Shared Real Property in which such Co-Owner has an Ownership Interest; provided that, subject to the provisions of Section 13.1.4, if such Co-Owner is not the Operator, it shall (i) provide reasonable notice to Operator, and (ii) not unreasonably interfere with Operator???s operation, maintenance or repair of the Shared Facilities or of another Co-Owner???s Facility.
ARTICLE IV -- OWNERSHIP OF AND RIGHT TO USE SHARED ASSETS
4.1 Ownership Interests. On the date that all conditions precedent set forth in Section 4.2.3 below applicable to such Co-Owner (if any), are satisfied (the ???CP Satisfaction Date???), such Co-Owner owns or shall own an undivided interest in the applicable Shared Assets Group as described in Exhibit C in such applicable Shared Assets Group (such undivided interest of each Co-Owner being referred to in this Agreement as its ???Ownership Interest???). If applicable, a Co-Owner shall provide to the Operator and to the other Co-Owners in the same Shared Assets group written notice that the CP Satisfaction Date has occurred.
4.2 Undivided Use Interests. Each Co-Owner who has an Ownership Interest in a Shared Asset Group shall have an undivided right to the use or capacity of the applicable Shared Assets equal to its Ownership Interest therein (such undivided use interest of a Co-Owner is referred to in this Agreement as its ???Undivided Use Interest???).
4.2.1 Shared Transmission Line. Each Co-Owner of a Shared Transmission Line shall be entitled to use its Undivided Use Interest in the Delivery Capability of the Shared Transmission Line. In the event that the Delivery Capability of the Shared Transmission Line exceeds the capability provided in the applicable Interconnection Agreement, with Transmission Owner???s and Transmission Provider???s written consent and approval, each Co-Owner???s Undivided Use Interest will be increased pro rata in accordance with its Ownership Interest for so long as the Delivery Capability is in excess of the capability provided in the Interconnection Agreements. For the avoidance of doubt, the Co-Owners will not exceed the Maximum Facility Output, as defined in the applicable Interconnection Agreement, unless all necessary approvals and consents are obtained (including from Transmission Owner and Transmission Provider).
4.2.2 Excess Capability. No Co-Owner shall have the right to use more than its Undivided Use Interest of the Delivery Capability of the Shared Transmission Line or portion of the Shared Transmission Line. During periods in which a Co-Owner is not utilizing its full Undivided Use Interest in the Delivery Capability of the Shared Transmission Line or portion of Shared Transmission Line, the other Co-Owner may utilize more than its full Undivided Use Interest, subject to the operating limits of the Shared Facilities, so long as such usage does not interfere with or adversely affect the first Co-Owner???s energy schedules and deliveries; and provided that (i) prior to any Co-Owner using more than its Undivided Use Interest of the Delivery Capability of the Shared Transmission Line or portion of the Shared Transmission Line, the Co- Owners shall have obtained all necessary approvals from Governmental Authorities, including Federal Energy Regulatory Commission acceptance for filing of an effective transmission
3
services agreement for such usage to the extent required and (ii) no payment obligation will attach to such utilization by a Co-Owner of more than its full Undivided Use Interest.
4.2.3 Condition Precedent. The condition precedent to the CP Satisfaction Date shall be a date that is thirty (30) calendar days after: (i) Co-Owner 2 is granted a final order from the FERC pursuant to Section 205 of the Federal Power Act, as amended, authorizing the sale at wholesale of electric energy, capacity and ancillary services at market based rates, accepting a tariff providing for such sales and granting such waivers and blanket authorizations as are customarily granted by FERC; (ii) each of the Co-Owners have filed the Agreement with FERC pursuant to Section 205 of the Federal Power Act, as amended, and such filing has become effective; (iii) Co- Owner 1 obtains written consent from LSU to assign Ownership Interest in the Shared Facilities to Co-Owner 2 pursuant to Article XVII of that certain Ground Lease Agreement for Solar Energy Generation dated August 1, 2016, as amended, by and between LSU and Co-Owner 1; (iv) has delivered an executed Assignment of Movables as set forth in Section 4.3 below and (v) has delivered the payment or payments as required pursuant to Section 4.3 below.
4.3 Reimbursement of Capital Costs. To compensate any Co-Owner (each, a ???Reimbursee???), in each respective Shared Assets Group for having borne a disproportionate share of the costs and expenses of design, procurement, construction, installation and/or startup of the applicable Shared Assets in the respective Shared Assets Group, the Reimbursee shall be reimbursed by the other applicable Co- Owners in such Shared Asset Group (each, a ???Reimbursor???), for such costs based on the depreciated book-value the applicable Shared Assets in the respective Shared Assets Group agreed upon by the applicable Co-Owners in accordance with their respective Ownership Interests, as of the CP Satisfaction Date of the Reimbursor. In connection with such reimbursement, the Reimbursee shall execute an Assignment of Movables for the benefit of each Reimbursee in accordance with their respective Ownership Interests substantially in the forms set forth herein as Exhibit F and Exhibit G, respectively.
4.4 Additional Phases. A Co-Owner or its Affiliate shall have the right to build and operate an additional phase or phases (an ???Additional Phase???), to connect such Additional Phase (or such portion of the Additional Phase as may be compatible with Transmission Owner???s interconnection facilities), to the Shared Facilities and to use the Shared Assets, subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement. The owner of such Additional Phase shall execute a joinder, the form of which is attached as Exhibit E hereto (the ???Joinder???), and the Co-Owners shall execute an appropriate amendment to this Agreement to reflect the Ownership Interest of the Additional Phase in the applicable Shared Assets Groups. In addition, and in connection with the amendment, the Co-Owner of the Additional Phase shall execute an Assignment of Movables and reimburse any applicable Reimbursee as set forth in Section 4.3 above. Notwithstanding anything contained herein to the contrary, the owner of the Additional Phase shall bear any incremental costs and expenses of modifying and upgrading the applicable existing Shared Facilities to accommodate the connection of its Facility.
4.5 Initial Connection to Shared Facilities.
4.5.1 In connection with the initial interconnection of any Facility (a ???Connecting Facility???) to any of the Shared Facilities, the Co-Owner that owns such Connecting Facility (the ???Connecting Co-Owner???) shall be responsible for (and for all initial costs in respect of), the initial interconnection of such Connecting Facility to the Shared Facilities (the ???New Connection???). Each Connecting Co-Owner acknowledges and agrees that the New Connection may result in (a) 4
damage to the Shared Facilities or any other Co-Owner???s Facility; (b) claims from third parties and (c) lost revenues associated with scheduled and/or unscheduled outages and/or curtailment of some or all of the energy production from the New Connection of the Connecting Facility to any other Co-Owner???s Facility (including the cash value of any lost federal production tax credits, grossed-up based on the actual federal income tax rate applicable to the applicable Co-Owner, penalties imposed on the applicable Co-Owner or damages payable by the applicable Co-Owner to a power purchaser, energy hedge provider or transmission service provider for the applicable Co-Owner???s Facility) (together with related costs and/or expenses, collectively, ???New Connection Losses???).
4.5.2 All New Connection Losses shall be the sole responsibility of the Connecting Co- Owner that owns the applicable Connecting Facility. As part of the process for implementation of any New Connection, the applicable Connecting Co-Owner shall establish a protocol to reasonably minimize disruptions to the Shared Facilities and any other Co-Owner???s Facility. Within ten (10) Business Days after receipt of written notice from the applicable Connecting Co- Owner that the applicable New Connection has been completed, each of the other Co-Owners shall reasonably determine its actual New Connection Losses and deliver reasonable backup documentation supporting the calculation thereof to the applicable the Connecting Co-Owner. The applicable Connecting Co-Owner shall pay to each other Co-Owner all undisputed New Connection Losses incurred by such Co-Owner within thirty (30) days following receipt of the calculation of New Connection Losses from such Co-Owner. Any disputed New Connection Losses incurred by any Co-Owner that are determined, to be owed by the applicable Connecting Co-Owner shall be payable by such Connecting Co-Owner to such other Co-Owner within thirty (30) days following such determination. Each Co-Owner shall have all other rights and remedies as may be provided in this Agreement or otherwise available at law or in equity resulting from any Connecting Co-Owner???s failure to pay any New Connection Losses.
ARTICLE V -- METERING, MEASUREMENT OF ENERGY DELIVERIES AND LOSSES
5.1 Measurement of Energy and Allocation of Losses. Energy transmitted on the applicable Shared Transmission Line shall be measured and allocated between the Co-Owners of the Shared Facilities as set forth on Attachment B-2 to Exhibit B. The Revenue Metering Diagram depicts and delineates several metering connections used to measure energy and allocate losses by and among the Facilities, and such metering calculations are used to determine the Facilities??? generated real power delivered to and received from the point of interconnect.
5.2 Testing and Repair of Co-Owner???s Meters.
5.2.1 Inspection and Testing. If applicable and in conformance with the applicable Interconnection Agreement(s), a Co-Owner will cause meters (other than revenue meters owned by the interconnection provider and check meters owned by the individual Co-Owner) to be inspected and tested upon its installation and at least once every twenty four (24) months thereafter and at any other reasonable time upon the other Co-Owner???s request, which may not be made more than three times in said twenty four (24) month period. The Co-Owner requesting such inspection and testing will pay the costs of same, unless the results of the test show the Co- Owner???s meter to be inaccurate by more than half of one percent (0.5%), in which case the Co-
5
Owners will share the costs of the test. Each Co-Owner will give the other Co-Owners reasonable advance notice of tests of its meter and the other Co-Owners have the right to witness such tests.
5.2.2 Calibration or Repair. If a test shows a Co-Owner???s meter to be inaccurate, the owner or owners of the meter will use reasonable efforts to cause its meter to be calibrated, repaired or replaced.
5.3 Back-Feed Power. The Co-Owners will arrange for the provision of back-feed power service for each of their Facilities.
ARTICLE VI -- OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF SHARED FACILITIES.
6.1 Engagement of Operator; Change of Control.
6.1.1 The Co-Owners hereby engage the Operator to manage, operate, maintain and repair the Shared Facilities and to perform other duties pertaining to the Shared Assets (the ???O&M Services???), all as set forth in this Agreement. The Operator accepts such engagement and agrees to perform such duties in accordance with the terms and conditions hereof. The Co-Owners hereby agree and acknowledge that the Operator may enter into one or more contracts with licensed third-party providers to perform the O&M Services.
6.1.2 In the event that there is a Change of Control of the Operator, the Operator hereby covenants and agrees to assign all of its rights, duties and obligations as Operator hereunder to the other Co-Owner and such other Co-Owner shall thereafter become the Operator. The Co- Owners shall cooperate with each other in effecting such transition and provide all notices to third parties and take all other actions deemed necessary or advisable by any of them with respect to such change in status. Effective as of the date of the assignment of the duties and obligations of Operator to the other Co-Owner pursuant to this Section 6.1.2, such Co-Owner shall assume responsibility for all obligations of the Operator thereafter accruing under this Agreement and the former Operator shall assume all obligations of a Co-Owner thereafter accruing under this Agreement.
6.2 Standards for Operator???s Performance. Operator shall perform or cause to performed the O&M Services in accordance with Good Utility Practice, the Material Project Agreements, the Real Property Agreements, this Agreement and all Applicable Laws and requirements of Governmental Authorities, including without limitation all Hazardous Materials Laws and all Environmental Laws, and all safety policies and procedures (collectively, the ???Performance Standard???).
6.3 O&M Services. The Operator shall provide or cause to be provided the following services on behalf of each of the Co-Owners who have an Undivided Use Interest from and after the date such Co-Owner has notified Operator of its exercised right to an Undivided Use Interest in the Shared Assets pursuant to Section 4.2 (the ???O&M Services Commencement Date???):
6.3.1 manage, supervise, operate, repair and maintain the Shared Assets, including the day to day management of the Shared Assets in accordance with Material Project Agreements?? Good Utility Practice and the Annual O&M Budget;
6
6.3.2 pay and collect amounts due in connection with the Shared Assets including but not limited to taxes and assessments pursuant to Section 12.2, and maintain one or more bank accounts wherein funds received by the Operator in connection with its duties herein shall be maintained;
6.3.3 expend monies necessary for the management, operation, maintenance and repair of the Shared Facilities;
6.3.4 notify every Co-Owner of any notice (or any other information reasonably anticipated to affect the Co-Owners) received by the Operator or received from any Co-Owner;
6.3.5 manage compliance with the Co-Owners??? rights in Shared Real Property in accordance with the Real Property Agreements, including making payments required thereunder; provided that the Operator shall have no right to amend such rights in the Shared Real Property; and
6.3.6 with respect to the Shared Real Property and the Shared Facilities located on the Shared Real Property, oversee all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any Governmental Authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to the use, operation or ownership of the Shared Real Property or the Shared Facilities locate on the Shared Real Property.
6.4 Scheduled Maintenance. Operator shall schedule, or cause to be scheduled, maintenance and any planned outages of the Shared Facilities so as to minimize interference with Co-Owners??? scheduled energy deliveries. Maintenance and any planned outages of the Shared Facilities shall be scheduled, to the maximum extent possible, during scheduled maintenance outages of the Co-Owners??? Facilities. Each Co-Owner will provide to the Operator and the other affected Co-Owners by January 1 of each year a schedule of planned maintenance outages on such Co-Owner???s Facility for the subsequent twelve- month period. Scheduled outages of the Shared Facilities will be subject to the mutual approval by the affected Co-Owners, such approval not to be unreasonably withheld. Operator will seek to limit the duration of any outage, planned or unplanned, consistent with Good Utility Practice.
6.5 Unplanned Outages. Operator will notify, or cause to be notified, Co-Owners of all emergency or unplanned outages of any of the Shared Facilities as soon as practicable, in accordance with Good Utility Practice, and will provide an estimated time of return of the Shared Facilities to service, or if not known, will keep, or cause to be kept, Co-Owners advised regarding the status of same.
6.6 Emergency Conditions. In the event of an Emergency Condition involving the Shared Assets that could be reasonably expected by Operator to result in possible personal injury, loss of life, damage to or destruction of property, or danger to the public, the Operator shall, without the need for prior notification of the Co-Owners, take such action, or cause such action, as may be reasonable and necessary, as determined in the sole discretion of the Operator, to prevent, avoid or mitigate such loss, and shall, as soon as reasonably practicable, report any such emergency, including the Operator???s response thereto, to the Co-Owners, and Operator, if allowed by law, be compensated by the Co-Owners for the costs of taking such actions in proportion to their Ownership Interest in the Shared Assets so affected.
7
6.7 O&M Costs. Costs of performing O&M Services (the ???O&M Costs???) shall be budgeted accordingly and include all payments made and expenses incurred by Operator in performing O&M Services (at cost and without markup), including but not limited to related overheads and applicable taxes, and costs (except insurance costs) related to ownership of the Shared Assets.
6.8 Budgeting Process. Each year during the term of this Agreement, Operator will prepare a forecast budget of O&M Costs for the following calendar year and will provide a copy to Co-Owners by December 1st. Co-Owners will have ten (10) days thereafter to review the forecast budget and discuss any concerns with the forecast budget with Operator, provided that following the 10-day period such forecast budget of O&M Costs shall be deemed approved if no concerns are identified in writing by the Co-Owners. Operator???s implementation of the O&M Services consistent with the forecast budget is subject to Co-Owners??? prior approval, not to be unreasonably withheld (such approved forecast budget, the ???Annual O&M Budget???)
6.9 Extraordinary Maintenance. Each Co-Owner agrees to reimburse Operator for its share, in proportion to its Undivided Use Interest, of the costs of any maintenance or other services required in the event of unusual or catastrophic circumstances, to the extent such costs were not included in the forecast budget for O&M Services and incurred by the Operator (???Extraordinary Maintenance???).
6.10 Responsibility for O&M Costs.
6.10.1 Each Co-Owner shall be responsible for its share, in proportion to its Undivided Use Interest, of O&M Costs, including its share of the costs of any Extraordinary Maintenance incurred by Operator, which shall be invoiced by Operator on a quarterly basis. On or before the tenth (10th) day following the end of each calendar quarter, Operator shall invoice Co-Owners for their respective Undivided Use Interest of 1/4 of the amount of the current Annual O&M Budget, along with the costs of any Extraordinary Maintenance performed in the previous quarter. The invoices shall be delivered to the parties identified in Section 17.15. Co-Owners shall pay such invoice within thirty (30) days of its receipt (the ???Due Date???). Any amounts not paid by the Due Date shall be deemed delinquent and shall accrue interest at the then-effective prime rate of interest published under ???Money Rates??? by The Wall Street Journal, plus two percent per annum from the Due Date to the date of payment (the ???Late Payment Rate???). For purposes of this Section 6.10 and for Section 6.11, ???receipt??? shall mean the date upon which the invoice is received in accordance with Section 17.15. In the event that any Due Date falls upon a weekend day or bank holiday, such payment shall be due and payable on the first Business Day immediately thereafter.
6.10.2 Within sixty (60) days after the end of each calendar year, Operator shall invoice the Co- Owners for, or shall refund to the Co-Owners, as applicable, their Ownership Interest of the difference between the sum of the Annual O&M Budget and the costs of any Extraordinary Maintenance and the actual amount of O&M Costs paid or incurred in such calendar year. Any invoice for such amounts shall be paid within the Due Date. The invoices shall be delivered to Co-Owners as set forth in Section 17.15. Any amounts not paid when due shall be deemed delinquent and shall accrue interest at the Late Payment Rate. In the event that any due date falls upon a weekend day or bank holiday, such payment shall be due and payable on the first Business Day immediately thereafter
8
6.11 Disputes. If a Co-Owner disputes the accuracy of all or any portion of an invoice, such Co-Owner shall, nevertheless, pay the undisputed portion of the amount owing on the invoice and submit to Operator a written statement detailing the items and amount disputed. If Co-Owner prevails with respect to the disputed amounts, Operator shall refund Co-Owner the disputed amounts, including interest on the disputed amounts at the Late Payment Rate.
6.12 Curtailment. Unless directed otherwise by the Transmission Provider or any Governmental Authority or regulatory authority having jurisdiction over the Shared Facilities, the Operator shall allocate curtailment orders such that each Facility???s transmission capacity on the Shared Facilities is curtailed on a pro rata basis in accordance the Co-Owner of such Facility???s Undivided Use Interest of the Delivery Capability of the Shared Transmission Line; provided, however, that with respect to any Facility that does not use all of its capacity so curtailed, such unused capacity will be allocated to the other Facility on a pro rata basis in accordance with such Co-Owner of such Facility???s Undivided Use Interest of the Delivery Capability of the Shared Transmission Line.
6.13 No Waiver of Right to Audit. Any payment made by a Co-Owner pursuant to this Agreement shall not constitute a waiver of any right of such Co-Owner to question or contest the accuracy of any charge, or to request and receive from Operator sufficient data to audit any charge concerning which a Co-Owner has a question or which is or may be contested, provided, however, that Co-Owner must initiate any audit or data request no later than twelve (12) months after the Due Date of any such bill or charge and bear reasonable costs associated with such audit, and provided further that if as a result of the audit a determination is made that errors were made by Operator, Operator shall, in addition to correcting the error, reimburse the costs of the audit to the Co-Owners.
6.14 Obligations. The Operator shall have no liability for any obligations except those expressly stated in this Agreement, and nothing in this Agreement shall obligate the Operator to perform any duties or assume any liabilities under any agreement to which the Operator is not directly a party unless such duties are also expressly stated in this Agreement, and then only to such extent. The Co- Owners acknowledge that the Operator???s performance under this Agreement is dependent upon the Co- Owners having complied with their obligations under this Agreement and the Operator having timely and appropriate access to all parts of the Shared Assets and access to all documents as reasonably required by the Operator.
6.15 Major Decisions. The Operator shall not, without the prior written consent of the Co- Owners: (i) cause or allow the sale, lease, lien, encumbrance or other voluntary disposition of the Shared Facilities or Shared Real Property; (ii) enter into any amendment or modification to the Material Project Agreements; (iii) take any action that would materially and adversely change the regulatory status of the Facilities or Co-Owners; or (iv) make any material capital expenditures, except in the case of Extraordinary Maintenance.
ARTICLE VII -- DAMAGE OR DESTRUCTION OF SHARED FACILITIES
7.1 Damage or Destruction. In the event of any damage or destruction to or other failure of all or any part of the Shared Facilities that affects the business operations of one or more Co-Owners in a Shared Assets Group (each an ???Affected Party???), such Affected Party shall, subject to any contrary requirements set forth in Material Project Agreements or by Applicable Law, take all commercially reasonable actions as may be necessary or appropriate to repair or replace the affected Shared Facilities 9
in order to restore the affected Shared Facilities to substantially the same condition (or better) as before such damage or destruction and, subject to Section 15.2 below, any costs associated with such actions, after accounting for recoveries under any applicable insurance policies, will be shared by the Co-Owners pro rata based on their Ownership Interests, as applicable. Following any such damage, destruction or failure, if (i) the Affected Party fails to diligently proceed with the repair or replacement of the affected Shared Facilities in accordance with the preceding sentence or (ii) the Affected Party notifies the other affected Co-Owners that it does not intend to repair or replace the affected Shared Facilities, then in either such case, the other affected Co-Owners shall have the right to repair or replace the affected Shared Facilities (or a portion thereof sufficient to serve such other Co-Owners??? requirements) and continue the operation and maintenance thereof for the remainder of the Term; provided, that in such event and subject to Section 15.2 below, the Affected Party shall be obligated to the Co-Owners funding the repair or replacement of the Shared Facilities for the costs of repair or replacement on a pro rata basis based on its Ownership Interest; and provided further, that such other Co-Owners shall not unreasonably interfere with the business operations of the Affected Party. In all events, the Co-Owners shall cooperate with each other in good faith to minimize the impact thereof on the Co-Owners and their respective business operations.
ARTICLE VIII -- CESSATION OF OPERATIONS BY A CO-OWNER
8.1 Co-Owner Ceasing Operations. In the event a Co-Owner anticipates shutting down, decommissioning, abandoning or ceasing the business operations of its Facility, (such Co-Owner, a ???Co- Owner Ceasing Business Operations???), it shall provide the other Co-Owners with at least six (6) months??? prior written notice of such planned shut-down, abandonment, decommissioning, or cessation of business operations, which shall indicate whether or not such Co-Owner Ceasing Business Operations relinquishes any option to rebuild its facilities or otherwise restart its operations within six (6) months after such cessation. Sunlight Road Solar, L.L.C.
Market-Based Rate Wholesale Power Sale Tariff
1. Availability. Sunlight Road Solar, L.L.C. ("Seller") makes electric energy, capacity, and ancillary services available under this Tariff to any purchaser for resale. 2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all sales of capacity, energy, or ancillary services by Seller not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule. 3. Rates. All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions of sales shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 5. Ancillary Services. Seller may make available to any purchaser the following ancillary services. a. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. b. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. c. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. d. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. e. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (MISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. f. Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (SPP) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. g. Third Party Provider: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider???s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 6. Compliance with Commission Regulations. Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff. 7. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority. Seller has received (i) waiver of the accounting and reporting requirements contained in 18 C.F.R. Parts 41, 101 (with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licensees is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects), and 141, except for section 141.15; (ii) waiver of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subparts B and C, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15, and 35.16; and (iii) blanket authorization under 18 C.F.R. Part 34 of all future issuances of securities and assumption of liabilities. See Sunlight Road Solar, L.L.C., Docket No. ER24-847-000 (2024). Seller???s tariff excludes market-based sales to customers located within the Puget Sound Energy Balancing Authority Area. See Puget Sound Energy, Inc., 181 FERC ?? 61,008 (2022). 8. Mitigated Sales. Sales of energy and capacity are permissible under this tariff in all balancing authority areas where the Seller has been granted market-based rate authority. Sales of energy and capacity under this tariff are also permissible at the metered boundary between the Seller's mitigated balancing authority area and a balancing authority area where the Seller has been granted market-based rate authority provided: (i) legal title of the power sold transfers at the metered boundary of the balancing authority area where the seller has market-based rate authority; and (ii) if the Seller sells at the metered boundary of a mitigated balancing authority area at market-based rates, then neither it nor its affiliates can sell into that mitigated balancing authority area from the outside. Seller must retain, for a period of five years from the date of the sale, all data and information related to the sale that demonstrates compliance with items (i) and (ii) above. 9. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 1 seller in the Northeast, Northwest, Southeast, Southwest and Southwest Power Pool regions, as defined by 18 CFR ?? 35.36(a). Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Central region, as defined by 18 CFR ?? 35.36(a).
